data.content:
Three breaking changes hit your code. Here's each one and the fix:

---

### 1. `ExecuteUpdateAsync` — no longer takes an expression tree

The setters parameter changed from `Expression<Func<...>>` to `Func<...>`. Your manual expression-tree building **won't compile**.

**Fix** — replace the entire block with a simple lambda:

```csharp
await context.Blogs.ExecuteUpdateAsync(s =>
{
    s.SetProperty(b => b.Views, 8);
    if (nameChanged)
    {
        s.SetProperty(b => b.Name, "foo");
    }
});
```

No more `Expression.Lambda`, `Expression.Call`, etc. Conditional setters just use normal `if` statements now.

---

### 2. Complex type column names — two changes

**a) Duplicate names are now auto-uniquified.** `ShippingAddress.Street` and `BillingAddress.Street` previously shared one `Street` column silently (data corruption risk). EF 10 appends a number (`Street`, `Street1`).

If you have an existing database and want to **keep the old shared column**, pin it explicitly:

```csharp
modelBuilder.Entity<Customer>(b =>
{
    b.ComplexProperty(c => c.ShippingAddress,
        p => p.Property(a => a.Street).HasColumnName("Street"));
    b.ComplexProperty(c => c.BillingAddress,
        p => p.Property(a => a.Street).HasColumnName("Street"));
});
```

If they should have been separate columns all along, generate a new migration — EF will now create distinct columns automatically.

**b) Nested complex types use full path in column names.** `Order.Payment.BillingAddress.City` previously mapped to `BillingAddress_City`, now maps to `Payment_BillingAddress_City`.

To keep old names, pin explicitly:

```csharp
modelBuilder.Entity<Order>()
    .ComplexProperty(o => o.Payment)
    .ComplexProperty(p => p.BillingAddress)
    .Property(a => a.City)
    .HasColumnName("BillingAddress_City");
```

> **For both**: if you're generating a migration after upgrading, inspect it carefully for unexpected column renames.

---

### 3. `IRelationalCommandDiagnosticsLogger` — new `logCommandText` parameter

Every method gained a `string logCommandText` parameter (supports redacted SQL logging).

**Fix** — add the parameter to your implementation:

```csharp
public class MyLogger : IRelationalCommandDiagnosticsLogger
{
    public InterceptionResult<DbDataReader> CommandReaderExecuting(
        IRelationalConnection connection,
        DbCommand command,
        DbContext context,
        Guid commandId,
        Guid connectionId,
        DateTimeOffset startTime,
        string logCommandText)       // ← new parameter
    {
        // Use logCommandText for logging (constants may be redacted)
        // Use command.CommandText for the actual SQL sent to the DB
    }
}
```

Update **all** methods on the interface (`CommandReaderExecuted`, `CommandScalarExecuting`, etc.) the same way.
